quarks.window

Interface Window<T,K,L extends java.util.List<T>>

  • Type Parameters:
    T - type of tuples in the window
    K - type of the window's key
    L - type of the list used to contain tuples.

    public interface Window<T,K,L extends java.util.List<T>>
    Partitioned window of tuples. Conceptually a window maintains a continuously changing subset of tuples on a stream, such as the last ten tuples or tuples that have arrived in the last five minutes.

    Window is partitioned by keys obtained from tuples using a key function. Each tuple is inserted into a partition containing all tuples with the same key (using equals()). Each partition independently maintains the subset of tuples defined by the windows policies.
    An unpartitioned is created by using a key function that returns a constant, to force all tuples to be inserted into a single partition. A convenience function unpartitioned() is provided that returns zero as the fixed key.

    The window's policies are flexible to allow any definition of what tuples each partition will contain, and how the partition is processed.

    • Method Detail

      • insert

        boolean insert(T tuple)
        Attempts to insert the tuple into its partition. Tuple insertion performs the following actions in order:
        1. Call K key = getKeyFunction().apply(tuple) to obtain the partition key.
        2. Get the partition for key creating an empty partition if one did not exist for key.
        3. Apply the insertion policy, calling getInsertionPolicy().apply(partition, tuple). If it returns false then return false from this method, otherwise continue.
        4. Apply the contents policy, calling getContentsPolicy().apply(partition, tuple). This is a pre-insertion action that allows any action. Some policies may request room to be made for the insertion by calling evict() which will result in a call to the evict determiner.
        5. Add tuple to the contents of the partition.
        6. Apply the trigger policy, calling getTriggerPolicy().apply(partition, tuple). This is a post-insertion that action allows any action. A typical implementation is to call partition.process() to perform processing of the window.
        Parameters:
        tuple -
        Returns:
        true, if the tuple was successfully inserted. Otherwise, false.

      • getEvictDeterminer

        Consumer<Partition<T,K,L>> getEvictDeterminer()
        Returns the window's eviction determiner. The evict determiner is responsible for determining which tuples in a window need to be evicted.
        Calls to Partition.evict() result in getEvictDeterminer().accept(partition) being called. In some cases this may not result in tuples being evicted from the partition.

        An evict determiner evicts tuples from the partition by removing them from the list returned by Partition.getContents().

        Returns:
        evict determiner for this window.
